[% META
   title = "Logging Settings"
   description = "Configure application logging and alert levels"
   roles = "admin"
   TemplateType = "Application"
   category = "Admin"
   page_version = "0.01"
   last_updated = "2026-03-08"
%]
[% PageVersion = 'admin/Logging/AdminLoggingSettings.tt,v 0.01 2026/03/08 Zencoder Exp Zencoder' %]
[% IF debug_mode == 1 %]
  [% PageVersion %]
[% END %]

<div class="app-container">
    <div class="page-header">
        <h1>Logging Settings</h1>
    </div>

    [% IF error_msg %]<div class="error">[% error_msg | html %]</div>[% END %]

    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="content-primary">
            
            <div class="form-container">
                <form method="post" action="[% c.uri_for('/admin/logging/settings') %]" class="app-form">
                    
                    <div class="form-section">
                        <h3>File Logging</h3>
                        <p class="help-text">
                            Write logs to <code>logs/application.log</code> on the app server disk.
                            <strong>Disable in production</strong> to prevent disk fill-up — WARN/ERROR entries
                            still go to the database and STDERR (Docker container logs) regardless.
                        </p>
                        [% SET fl_on = file_logging_enabled ? 1 : 0 %]
                        <div class="form-row">
                            <div class="form-field">
                                <label>Current status:</label>
                                <strong style="color:[% fl_on ? '#2e7d32' : '#c62828' %]">
                                    [% fl_on ? '✓ Enabled — writing to disk' : '✗ Disabled — STDERR + DB only' %]
                                </strong>
                                <br><small>Environment default: <code>[% env_default | html %]</code>
                                [% IF db_file_logging.defined %] · DB override: <code>[% db_file_logging == '1' ? 'enabled' : 'disabled' %]</code>[% END %]
                                </small>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="form-row" style="margin-top:8px">
                            <button type="submit" name="file_logging" value="[% fl_on ? '0' : '1' %]"
                                    class="btn [% fl_on ? 'btn-danger' : 'btn-success' %]"
                                    onclick="return confirm('[% fl_on ? 'Disable file logging? Log writes will go to DB + STDERR only.' : 'Enable file logging? A server restart is required for the log file to be created.' %]')">
                                [% fl_on ? 'Disable File Logging' : 'Enable File Logging' %]
                            </button>
                            <small style="margin-left:8px;color:#888">
                                Disabling takes effect immediately. Enabling takes effect on next restart
                                (so the log file and directory are created).
                            </small>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="form-section">
                        <h3>Alert Threshold</h3>
                        <p class="help-text">Select the minimum log level that should trigger an email notification to administrators.</p>
                        
                        <div class="form-row">
                            <div class="form-field">
                                <label for="email_threshold">Alert Level (Email/System):</label>
                                <select name="email_threshold" id="email_threshold" class="form-input">
                                    [% FOREACH level IN levels %]
                                        <option value="[% level | html %]" [% IF level == current_threshold %]selected[% END %]>[% level | html %]</option>
                                    [% END %]
                                </select>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="form-section">
                        <h3>NFS Log Directory</h3>
                        <p class="help-text">Specify the path to the NFS shared directory for centralized logging.</p>
                        
                        <div class="form-row">
                            <div class="form-field">
                                <label for="nfs_dir">NFS Path:</label>
                                <input type="text" name="nfs_dir" id="nfs_dir" value="[% current_nfs_dir | html %]" class="form-input" placeholder="/mnt/nfs/comserv/logs">
                                <small>Environment variable: <code>[% env_nfs_dir | html %]</code> (Current fallback)</small>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="form-actions">
                        <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">Save Settings</button>
                        <a href="[% c.uri_for('/admin/logging') %]" class="btn btn-secondary">Cancel</a>
                    </div>
                    
                </form>
            </div>

            <div class="content-section">
                <h3>Notes</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Alerts are sent to the CSC Admin and Site Admin (if different).</li>
                    <li>These settings are stored in the database (<code>site_config</code> table) and persist across restarts.</li>
                    <li>NFS logging is optional for redundant history. If configured and writable, the application will maintain a physical log file there.</li>
                    <li>The Database is the primary source for the Logging Administration search and filter features.</li>
                    <li><strong>File logging is automatically off in production</strong> (<code>CATALYST_ENV=production</code>) to prevent disk fill-up. You can override this here; disabling takes effect immediately, enabling requires a server restart to create the log file.</li>
                    <li>Regardless of file logging, <strong>WARN and above always go to the database</strong> and to Docker container logs (STDERR).</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>
</div>
